  <span id="freeText4687922858552264872" style="display:none"><br />It’s not a book, it’s a piece of literature; transcending time and space and boundaries created by nature and humans. Trying to script a story of two leads, one who is telling the story and the other whose story is being told, that spans over a distance of centuries, must not have been an easy task for Malouf. Written in peotic French, Malouf divided this small book of some 300 pages into four sections. First two dealing with the legend of Khayyam and his exploits across the Orient, last two dedicated to the narrator’s attempt to understand that very Orient by searching Khayyam in the places he came from. <br /><br />This book is a piece of history and yet it’s not. It’s a lesson on the Orient and yet it’s something else altogether. It’s a story on the legend of what Omar Khayyam was, but not as an astrologer or a mathematician, but as a poet and philosopher. As the narrator searches for the truth behind the legend, the thirst for Khayyam and his Rubbaiyat created through this book is not quenched but enhanced many more times by the time you read the last line. You don’t want it to end. You want more. You want answers, but there are none. <br /><br />Don’t read it for a story, read it for a web Malouf created around the magic of Persia and one of its greatest pearl, namely Omar Khayyam.<br /><br />But I want more!!!</span>
