  <span id="freeText5010484780511502703" style="display:none"><b>Samarkand</b>, the most beautiful face the Earth has ever turned towards the sun<br /><br />I have had to distance myself from people in order to hear the voice of my memory, to nurture a naive hope and insistent vision<br /><br />I am not one of those for whom faith is simply fear of judgement<br /><br />How do I pray? <br /><br />I study a rose, I count the stars, I marvel at the beauty of creation and how perfectly ordered it is<br /><br />We live in the age of the secret and of fear<br /><br />You must have two faces<br /><br />Show one to the crowd, and keep the other for yourself and your Creator<br /><br />She lifted it a little more and cast a glance which Omar noticed<br /><br />It was a moment too fleet to be detected by the crowd but an eternity for the lover<br /><br />Time has two faces, Khayyam said to himself<br /><br />It has two dimensions, its length is measured by the rhythm of the sun but its depth by the rhythm of passion<br /><br />Poetry lives in complete calm through the centuries<br /><br />The only veil I am wearing is the night<br /><br />How many nights had fate granted them?<br /><br />Their every kiss carried with it a taste of farewell, their every embrace a breathless flight<br /><br />God has made us fall in love just as he has made certain flowers poisonous<br /><br />I knew that I was going to cry this evening, but I did not know I would cry such bitter tears<br /><br />Look at me, Omar<br /><br />Look at me for the last time! <br /><br />Remember, I am your lover<br /><br />You loved me and I loved you<br /><br />Can you still recognize me?<br /><br />You can hide your writings, but not your tears<br /><br />I will not change my route because of my name, and I will not change my name because of my route<br /><br />The idea had been waiting for him there<br /><br />Both Paradise and Hell are in you<br /><br />Together, and different<br /><br />For Omar, life was different<br /><br />It was the pleasure of science and the science of pleasure<br /><br />Life is like a fire<br /><br />Flames which the passer-by forgets. Ashes which the wind scatters<br /><br />Do not look back, do not say goodbye, do not even collect your belongings<br /><br />You will compose your poems and I shall observe my stars<br /><br />The world will cease to exist for us<br /><br />The wind from <b>Isfahan</b> carried a sharp perfume of apricot. But how lifeless were the streets!<br /><br />There was no music, not a sound, no secrets<br /><br />-<br /><br />It could just be a simple coincidence that we were reading the same book<br /><br />Omar appeared to us instantly like fate’s password<br /><br />If sweetness had a colour, it would be hers<br /><br />God, she was beautiful<br /><br />My first image of the Orient – a woman such as only the desert poet knew how to praise: <br /><br />Her face was the sun, they would have said<br /><br />Her hair the protecting shadow, her eyes fountains of cool water, her body the most slender of palm-trees and her smile a mirage<br /><br />In the cities of the Orient, one always looks for the colours of the present and the shades of the past<br /><br /><b>Teheran</b> had too short a history!<br /><br />We debated and constructed a thousand gloomy futures<br /><br />The future was no more than a forbidden dream<br /><br />Poems which dealt with a wisdom which was so accurate or a beauty so timeless<br /><br />There were words of heartache and consolation, the touching monologue of a defeated and dignified poet<br /><br />But there were also words of joy and sublime<br /><br />She looked deep into my eyes, as if she were reading an open book<br /><br />She had understood everything and sighed<br /><br />Once freed, <b>Samarkand</b> will be able to tell us its history<br /><br />Everything from that time has been destroyed – as if by a curse<br /><br />Walls, palaces, orchards, gardens and books<br /><br />There is the city which is buried under the ground<br /><br /><b>Samarkand</b> thus became the symbol of the inescapable meeting between man and his destiny<br /><br />The Orient, the place of all wonders and unfathomable nostalgia<br /><br />Shireen!<br /><br />Was it the way I uttered her name?<br /><br />The Titanic was now in a vertical position and its lights had dimmed<br /><br />The manuscript was our reason for being together<br /><br />Today I wonder: Did she exist? <br /><br />Was she anything other than the fruit of my oriental obsessions?<br /><br />The Rubaiyaat on the Titanic! <br /><br />Khayyam, if you could only see what a beautiful moment has been granted to us!</span>
