  <span id="freeText10424897048257642684" style="display:none">If you have never read Amin Maalouf before, then I recommend starting with "Samarkand". It contains real historical events, real characters and rich of details, and reading it is a real pleasure.<br /><p> <b> The novel is divided into two parts: </b> <br />  1- The story happened in the 11th century and which tells the era of Nizam Al-Mulk and the everyday life of Omar Al-Khayam(the poet).<br /> 2- The second is in 19 century where Benjamin O. Lesage (a passionate about quatrains of Omar AL Khayam) who tells us his quest for the lost manuscript of the poet. <br /><br />**********************************<br /> Like a pleasant voyage, "Samarkand" is a captivating novel that I had read with constant passion and curiosity. <br />I don't remember feeling bored during my reading, I was completely soaked in the Persian ambience and was dreaming of lying under an orange tree in one of the Persian gardens; thanks to Amin Maalouf's mastery of the description. </p><br />Throughout the chapters, you will find some verses of the quatrains of Omar AL-khayam (Ar-Rubaä'iyat - الرباعيات). <br />Although, I'm not sure these quatrains are the authentic ones. I have read that several poets have attributed their poems to Al-Khayyam for fear of being convicted because of their blasphemous content. <br />In short, everything that is published today in the name of Omar Alkhayam is not necessarily his.<br /><br /> <i> <b> PS : (without doubting the research and credibility of the author). </b> </i></span>
