  <span id="freeText10881622528498323392" style="display:none">Samarakand. A story of the same land, in two different eras. The first half of the novel tells us the journey of the wise Omar son of Ibrahim Khayyam. Ghyathud Din Abu El fath Omar ibn Ibrahim Khayyam was a persian 11th century philosopher, mathematician, astronomer and a poet. He is known for his Rubayiat رباعيات, the quatrains, a collection of poems consisting of 4 lines. But he also had great contributions to mathematics, especially concerning the resolution of cubic equations (equations with x to the power 3 ). The fact that we use x in mathematical equations today is thanks to him: In fact, he used the word "chay" شيء , which means "something", to represent the unknown variable. This word latinized, became "xay", then europeans started using only the first letter "x". He is also known for creating a new solar calendar called "the jalali calendar". Omar lived in the time of the seljukid sultanat, a turkic empire that expanded from anatolia to Transoxania and rulled persia. But the de facto ruler was the wise and powerful persian Vizier Nizamulmulk, who tried to build a powerful empire, by building schools, but also by creating a deadly order, both those works beared his name "nizamiah". Nizamulmulk's nemesis, was Hassan Sabbah, the man of Qom whose name brings fear and terror. For he was the founder of the deadliest brotherhood of history, The order of the Assassins. Omar Khayyam lived through a journey of love, sadness, darkness and wine, in a world of plots and intrigues between people he knew, and maybe even loved. Between Nizam, Hassan, The sultan Malikshah and his wife Terken Khatun, and his own lover and wife Jahan. A journey where he learned that life and fate are not something he can hold, not something he can guarantee, and that no matter what he did, he could not change the course of events or prevent the worse from happening.<br /><br />The second part of the novel takes us centuries later. To the beginning of the 20th century. The land where civilzation and sciences once flourished, endured hundreds of years of deep slumber, to wake up in a modern time that was way ahead of its own. Finding itself torn to pieces by foreign powers that suck its blood, taking humiliating privilges from its own monarchs, who would gladly give their country like a cake in order to keep absolute power. In this part, we follow Ben Lesage, the person who tells us the story of Khayyam and his Rubayiat in the first part. In a tumultous odyssey, Ben meets revolutionary personnalities from the history of Iran such as Jamaleddin Afghani and Mirza Reza Kermani. And joined the constitutional revolution of Iran alongside Howard Baskerville against the despotic shah. It is a journey that exposes the imperialist ways of russia and great britain to make a new democracy collapse. An adventure that shows how wise Khayyam was when he understood life 9 centuries before : " the sky is the chess player, and we are but the pawns,... it places us and replaces us, and then throw us in the well of nothingness", " You ask why is life so frail, so vain... I will make it plane, it is but a breath blown from the vasty deeps, And then blown back to those same deeps again" .<br /><br /><br />Edit : the following part is about a discussion about the charachter Shireen. There might be spoilers<br /><br />Discussing the novel with the person I love, we were talking about princess Shireen. Her charachter is interesting and clearly Maalouf wanted her to represent something. Princess Shireen Qajar is an imaginary charachter, we know very little about her. She is the granddaughter of the shah Nassereddin Qajar, and her uncles come from the bakhtyaris tribes. Other than that, she makes little appearences and fades again. Fazel, Jamalleddin, Mirza Reza were more present than the person Benjamin Omar Lesage fell in love with, isn't it a bit strange? We meet her in Istanbul when she was around 18 years old, she was one of Jamaleddine's disciples, but the meeting is brief and she disappears until she appears in other brief scenes, when major events happen. She is there when the shah got killed and helped Benjamin escape, and when the rise of the east starts to happen when people gathered in the british legation, she was the one relating to Benjamin those events. And she appears again when The constitutional resistants were at war against the cossacks and the shah, providing her palace for them to organize their plans, but also being Ben's lover and reading the Rubaiyat with him. It appears then that she represents Ben's own love and interest of the east. His interest in knowing the evolution of events. Him joining forces to fight a war that doesn't look like his. And of course his love for persian culture and traditions and Khayyam's poetry. This interest seems to fade in a sad way, when after all these efforts, the cause is lost, (the interest) disappears for ever, and nothing stays of it but some souvenirs, that he even question whether they were real or only the fruit of his own imagination, his own "Mirage of happiness" as the person I love called it. The name Shireen means sweet in persian, perhaps this name itself has a role. Maybe to represent how Ben loved Persia and its cause, that he found a sweetness in his engagement on it. <br />Another thing that I thought about, is that Shireen maybe represents Persia's struggle and its spirit wanting to become modern and progressive, by fighting to throw absolute monarchy and the tutorship of foreign powers on it, and create its own democracy. While at the same time, it is so into preserving its past, its culture and history. The same Iran that struggles to follow the 20th century, still doesn't want to leave some traditions that it gave the first prime minister in its history, Malkom Khan, the tiltle "Nizamulmulk". And Shireen represents this by the responsibility she felt about preserving Khayyam's manuscript, and by how she always refused leaving Iran with Ben to live in the US. Her attachement to the traditions appears especially, when she got terrified and superstitious about the dark pesimistic quatrain Ben read in the last chapter. A superstitious behaviour from a person who grew up in a modernist environment.</span>
