  <span id="freeText13524977883611378283" style="display:none">I had to read this book because of Omar Khayyam. A skillfully told tale between two times. The first in the times of Omar Khayyam; the great Persian mathematician, astrologist and poet and the story of the birth of his Rubaiyat. The 11th century Persia, when the cities of Samarkand and Bukhara were the greatest in the world. It is in Samarkand that Khayyam starts to compose the quatrains whose collection constitutes the immortal Rubaiyat. And in it he wrote:<br /><br /> “Samarkand, the most beautiful face the Earth has ever turned towards the sun”.<br /><br />The author's descriptions of the courts, the Bazaars, the life of kings is woven into a mystic tale; paralleling the fable of Hassan Bin Sabah, and the origin of his Assassins. I totally got lost in this story, the imagination was strong, the characters powerful with a bit of romance and hurt. <br />The second part of the book showcases the love of an American for Omar Khayyam, driven by love and curiosity, and a desire to find the lost manuscript of Omar Khayyam, and for that, he travels to Persia for two times, but got immersed in the ongoing dilemma of parliament that was established for the first time in Iran. The second half didn't appeal much, it was burdened with details I didn't wanna read after just going through the wonderful life of Omar Khayyam. <br /><br /><i> “We are the pawns, and Heaven is the player;<br />This is plain truth, and not a mode of speech.<br />We move about the chessboard of the world.<br />Then drop into the casket of the void.<br />And<br />Arise, we have eternity for sleeping. </i></span>
