  <span id="freeText12319759219619113605" style="display:none">A great story! I learned about the Rubaiyat, because I'm also interested in books about the Titanic disaster. More than once I read that the Rubaiyat had been on board. If it's true; I haven't figured that out yet. Some say yes it was, other say no it's hoax, the manuscript has vanished centuries ago. <br /><br />And now this great story. The first two part about the creation of the book and it's incredible travels are wonderful. Not only to know what happened to the book, but also to learn about Persia during time now long forgotten. <br />And then the last two parts. More contemporary, but as interesting and even more a page turner, because the historical events are spreading their long shadows up till today I think. I wonder, if the domination of Western countries in the Iranian/Persian affairs are still of influence in nowadays politics. I might be wrong, but I know from my history study, that after the decline of the Ottoman Empire the dominating Western countries divided the Middle-East in sphere of influence, mainly to protect their own economics and colonial imperialism. <br /><br />This book is historical fiction and the antagonists are no real people, but the book was composed so well, that I thought I was reading a novel, that happened the way Amin Maalouf has written it. <br /><br />I'm going to find a translation of the Rubaiyat and see if those quatrains will inspire me. <br /><br /><br /></span>
